    <p>
       Here is an image of the pictures on my living room wall. When you look at this, you'll notice the green wall between the pictures (that's the margin), the brown wood of the frames (the border) and the cream-colored mat between the picture and the frame (that's padding). 
    </p>
      
    <p>
       This is the easiest way I can think about these elements, <span class="bold">margins, padding and borders.</span> It's lucky for me that I've been an amateur photographer for decades so I not only took these pictures, I choose their mats and frames and hung them on the wall myself. So the idea setting up elements on a webpage in a way that is easier to read has this great visual analogy ten feet away from where I'm typing this.
    </p>

     <p>
       <span class="bold">Margins</span> set the space around the <span class="ital">outside</span> of an element.
    </p>

    <p>
       <span class="bold">Borders</span> go around the <span class="ital">edges</span> of the element.
    </p>
      
    <p>
       <span class="bold">Padding</span> is the space <span class="ital">around the contents </span> of your element. For example, you could set padding on a div to give some room around the paragraphs set inside of it.
    </p>
      
    <p>
      As with photographs, there are conventions to follow in setting elements on your webpage. Text is generally easier to read if there is some space around it (note also the indentation best-practices for coding). User experience will be more pleasant if images and other blocks of stuff are not just piled on the screen without any gaps.             
    </p>    

